There are quite a few. Navigation has accumulated many strategies because different environments fail in different ways. As metaphors for reasoning, each highlights a different mode of thinking.

Navigation Method	Reasoning Analogy	Strength	Weakness
Dead reckoning	Chain of inference	Works without external cues	Error compounds
Terrain association	Pattern recognition	Self-correcting	Requires recognizable landmarks
Map matching	Fit observations to a known model	Robust in familiar domains	Can force the wrong fit
Triangulation	Cross-check multiple independent facts	High confidence	Needs multiple reliable references
Landmark navigation	Use memorable anchor concepts	Fast and intuitive	Sparse landmarks can mislead
Compass heading	Follow a guiding principle or objective	Maintains direction	Doesn’t reveal obstacles
Celestial navigation	Orient using enduring invariants	Stable over long horizons	Lower precision locally
Pilotage	Navigate by continuous observation	Adaptive	Attention-intensive
Route following	Execute a known procedure	Reliable	Brittle outside the script
Exploration	Gather new information before deciding	Discovers opportunities	Slower
Homing	Return to a known reference state	Recovers from confusion	Doesn’t solve new problems
SLAM (Simultaneous Localization and Mapping)	Learn while reasoning	Builds new models	Computationally demanding
Bayesian localization	Continuously update confidence	Handles uncertainty well	Depends on good priors
Particle filter	Keep many hypotheses alive	Resilient to ambiguity	More complex
Graph search	Explore relationships systematically	Finds optimal paths	Needs a graph representation
Gradient following	Improve step by step	Efficient on smooth problems	Can get stuck locally
Constraint satisfaction	Narrow possibilities by eliminating conflicts	Precise	Can become combinatorially hard
Swarm navigation	Many simple agents explore together	Robust, parallel	Coordination overhead

